    Quiz nameIntroduction Location Timestamp
    Savvy Consumer of Family Science Savvy Consumer of Family Science Instructions People are often surprised to learn how frequently personal opinion, public opinion, public policy and law are influenced by family or other social science research. This is especially true when the research findings are widely published, as has been the case with the issues of "same-sex marriage". One of the most significant social issues of the last several centuries--one which divides our nation and the world almost right down the middle--is the issue of marriage. Until the last ten years no recorded civilization has ever considered marriage anything other than the union between a man and a woman. Now many are confused; private opinions are changing as individuals wonder whether their life-long assumptions and values are correct. Nations, communities and families are torn as to how to respond to the demands that marriage be redefined in a way never before considered possible. Much of the debate, including the debate and testimony in the United States Supreme Court, focuses of the effects such redefinition of marriage and family would have upon children. March 27, 2013, the Supreme Court Justices heard testimony on both sides of the issue stemming from California's Proposition 8. The proposition passed (twice) by California voters states simply that "only marriage between a man and a woman is valid or recognized in California.". The following day the Supreme Court heard arguments from the Obama administration, stating that the Defense of Marriage Act (DOMA) signed into law by President Clinton should not be enforced. DOMA states that the federal government will only recognize a marriage between a man and a woman.The current president refuses to enforce the law and has publicly come out against that law, while others argued that this law must be upheld by the President and his appointed agents. The Supreme Court Justices also read several briefs prepared by different individuals and organizations with the intention of summarizing large collections of data that would likely sway the justices' opinions. One such brief was prepared by the American Psychological Association (APA) in 2005. That brief was created and widely distributed "to serve the needs of psychologists, lawyers, and parties in family law cases....Although comprehensive, the research summary is focused on those issues that often arise in family law cases involving lesbian mothers or gay fathers" (APA Brief, 2005, p. 3) This brief included the assertion: "Not a single study has found children of lesbian or gay parents to be disadvantaged in any significant respect relative to children of heterosexual parents (p. 15). This brief has been used widely to change state and family law, and is not being presented to the court with the intent of changing national laws. Perhaps more importantly, the statements from the APA brief have also swayed media, educational, medical, and treatment organizations to adopt a similar position. It has also swayed numerous individuals who believe this to be the best informed collection of studies regarding the actual effects of changing family patterns upon the children. After all, it is argued, this brief represents the collective wisdom from the best-informed professionals, right? During the March 2013 hearings several of the Supreme Court Justices stated that they must focus largely upon how children are effected by the decisions they will make. So well-conducted research regarding the effects of same-sex ("gay" or "lesbian) parents should be have great effect upon whether the courts will allow marriage to be redefined. That makes family research very, very important. Another brief was filed and considered by the courts. Dr. Loren Marks wrote Same-sex parenting and children’s outcomes: A closer examination of the American Psychological Association’s brief on lesbian and gay parenting. This brief examines the validity of the research upon which the APA brief was based, and is sure to surprise most of its readers. Sadly, statements by some of the Supreme Court Justices made it clear that they did not review and understand the data presented to them. And the decisions made in 2013 greatly contributed to the decision of 5/9 of the justices to change the legal definition of marriage. This is an excellent opportunity to sharpen your skills in examining and explaining research in a way that helps you and others to make wise, informed decisions. Begin by scanning Marks' article (attached). Some parts might be a little difficult to wade through, especially if you are not accustomed to reviewing social science research. Focus on the highlighted sections. Explanatory/exploratory notes are also available by hovering over or clicking on the quote bubbles in the margins, but these will only be available to you if you download and then open the pfd document. After reviewing the article complete the quiz, in which you will demonstrate that you can discern your ability to discern between valid and less-valid research, and that you are prepared to be a savvy consumer of family science. Don't put the document away; you will need to use it throughout the "quiz". Also, print and bring the document with you to class to facilitate our discussion. You may take this quiz as many times as you like, and must take it until you get a score of 80% in order to move on in the course. Marks - Examination of APA Brief (anotated).pdf Copyright © 2016 by Brigham Young University - Idaho. All Rights Reserved. quiz-instructions\main.js 2018-06-15T15:52:28-06:00
    Mid-term Exam Midterm Exam Instructions This mid-term assessment will be a little different from most you have taken. Rather than asking you to repeat back specific terms and concepts you have read or discussed during the term you will be reading a recent opinion article from Dennis Prager, a well-respected commentator and radio talk show host in Los Angles. His article for the week discusses a current political issue facing the nation--and much of the western world. You will please read the article and then respond to several questions or prompts related to the topic. You will be asked to discuss your thinking on some of the questions, including why you responded as you did. Choose the very best answer in keeping with the principles you are learning in this course. You may take the exam up to three times; the highest score will be retained in the grade book. Why a Good Person Can Vote Against Same-Sex Marriage by Dennis Prager You may be interested to know that Mr. Prager does not consider same-sex attraction a choice of any sort, but has great sympathy for those who are simply born that way or otherwise drawn to be attracted to members of their own gender.     Blog Classmates Now Added Blog Lists Instructions Last week you created and modified a blog, then provided an address for that blog. It was/is required to have your lovely face on the landing page and to be set to allow anyone to comment on your blog, even anonymously. Now you must include your classmates' addresses in a convenient location on your blog. You may create a separate tab for that, or you can simply place a column with the names on your landing page. You choose the best option for you, but they must be available. The easiest way to accomplish this is to simply cut and paste the list our kind Teaching Assistant created for your convenience. You will find that address in the attached document. If you are a most experienced blogger you are welcome to use other tools (widgets, etc.) for making these names and addresses readily available for readers, including classmates, to explore if they so choose. When you have completed your work, you will need to submit your correct blog address/URL by opening and pasting the address into the assignment submission folder.
